---
import DocsLayout from '../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import Callout from '../../../../components/Callout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Deployment" description="Deploy to Netlify, get client sign-off, and verify the live staging site.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Deployment</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">You've built every ticket. Now ship it to a staging URL. You're deploying to Netlify's free tier — it connects to your GitHub repo, builds the site, and gives you a live URL. This is your staging environment — the version you show the client before going live.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4">Start the deploy ticket</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-2">The deploy ticket is in the backlog like any other ticket. Tell Claude:</p>
  <CodeBlock copy>{`Start Ticket 8.`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-2 mb-4">Claude will set up the Netlify connection and deploy. Once it's live, you'll have a real public URL — something like <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">your-project.netlify.app</code>.</p>

  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-3"><strong>Your verification focus:</strong></p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-4">
    <li>Open the live Netlify URL — does everything load?</li>
    <li>Test on your actual phone, not just DevTools mobile view</li>
    <li>Tap the phone number — does it open the dialer?</li>
    <li>Check that all links work on the live site (not just localhost)</li>
    <li>Run Lighthouse on the live URL — performance, SEO, accessibility</li>
  </ul>

  <details class="mb-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>Troubleshooting: "The deploy failed"</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Read the error message. Copy it. Paste to Claude: "The deploy failed with this error: [paste]. Fix it." You don't fix it — you communicate the error and direct the fix. This is directing.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What just happened</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Netlify is a <strong class="text-text">static hosting provider</strong>. It serves pre-built files — no server running your code, no database to maintain. That's why it can offer a free tier: serving static files is cheap. Vercel, Cloudflare Pages, and GitHub Pages work the same way. For a project like this, free hosting is the right choice.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">The <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">.netlify.app</code> URL is your staging environment. It's where you verify the site works in the real world — and it's what you show the client next.</p>

  <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Next: client review</h2>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Staging is live. Time to show the client and get sign-off.</p>
    <a
      href="/web-dev/projects/1/uat"
      class="inline-block bg-primary hover:bg-primary-dark text-white font-semibold py-3 px-6 rounded-md transition-colors min-h-[44px]"
    >
      UAT (User Acceptance Testing) →
    </a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
